article.description:
Jordan Hasquet had 20 points and 13
rebounds as Montana beat Northern Arizona 73-60 on its home floor
to win the Big Sky Conference championship and an NCAA Tournament
bid Wednesday night.
article.headline: Hasquet's double-double has Montana dancing
article.story: FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) -- The Montana Grizzlies celebrated their second consecutive NCAA Tournament berth to the blare of a fire alarm. After the Grizzlies' 73-60 victory over Northern Arizona here Wednesday night, sirens went off in the Walkup Skydome. The public address announcer asked everyone to leave the building, but the Grizzlies (23-6) weren't going anywhere until they accepted the Big Sky Conference tournament trophy and cut down the nets. It turned out to be a false alarm. But the Grizzlies' joy was real after whipping the Big Sky's regular-season champs on their home floor. "It's special," said head coach Larry Krystkowiak, who is 5-0 in Big Sky tourney games. "It's unbelievable." Freshman Jordan Hasquet had 20 points and 13 rebounds and Virgil Matthews added a game-high 21 points for the Grizzlies. Tyrone Bazy had 16 points and Steven Sir added 13 for top-seeded NAU (21-10), which is guaranteed an NIT berth as the Big Sky's regular-season champion. "Right now, the guys are so hurt," NAU coach Mike Adras said. "I don't want to shortchange the NIT because we're going to be a part of it. It's not the tournament we wanted to be in. But you know what? It's still an accomplishment for us to get our team into the postseason." The Grizzlies earned their seventh NCAA Tournament berth by dominating Northern Arizona on the boards -- Montana outrebounded NAU 44-27 -- and by refusing to fold when the Lumberjacks hit them with an 8-2 run to open the second half. For Montana, the Lumberjacks' burst brought back memories of an 83-80 loss here Jan. 19, when the Grizzlies blew a 19-point lead. This time, though, Krystkowiak called timeout and settled his players. "There was flashbacks, but we kept our composure this time," Hasquet said. Instead of dwelling on that collapse, the Grizzlies said they were fueled by their 96-83 victory over the Lumberjacks 10 days ago in Missoula. Hasquet scored 30 in that game. Northern Arizona had won 11 straight home games. But the Grizzlies weren't intimidated by a vocal crowd or affected by Flagstaff's 7,000-foot altitude, even after an overtime victory against Eastern Washington in the semifinal. "We thought we were the better team," Matthews said. Late in the first half, Montana broke the game open with a 12-0 run to take a 32-21 lead. The pivotal play came when Northern Arizona's Ruben Boykin Jr. blew a fastbreak dunk that would have given the Lumberjacks the lead. After that blunder, the Grizzlies ran off 10 points in 2:16. "Obviously, that would have energized our guys," Adras said. "It's a play that I know energizes Ruben, and it did just the opposite to him. That was a big momentum-changer in the first half." One night after they scored 98 points against Sacramento State, the Lumberjacks went cold. Senior Kelly Golob, the No. 3 scorer in school history, had more fouls (3) than field goals (2). He went 2-for-8 from the floor. "You have nights like that," Golob said. "Unfortunately, I picked one of the biggest games of my career to have one of those nights."
